Northrop Grumman is hosting a mentorship program targeting undergraduate students, with the kick off taking place virtually this Friday at 12pm.

Students can register via the Jacobs School Job & Internship Portal to receive the Zoom link. 

------------------------------------------

MentoriNG UCSD

Virtual kick off event on Friday, Oct 13th at 12pm - register here! 



Northrop Grumman cordially invites JSOE students to participate in our new mentorship program, MentoriNG UCSD. 

This is an opportunity to connect with NG professionals to learn more about the aerospace sector of the engineering world.
All majors are welcome, but in our work, there is an emphasis on electrical, computer, mechanical, and software engineering. 
Mentors will be current NG employees hailing from the San Diego area with a variety of specialties. 
This program will run throughout the Fall Quarter. Events will be limited to those students who are registered for the program. Students and mentors will be responsible for setting individual meetings throughout the quarter. 
NOTE: Due to the nature of the work, Northrop Grumman is not able to hire students who require visa sponsorship.

Join us to learn more about the program and meet potential NG mentors to help prepare for mentorship pairings!

After a brief intro to do’s and don’t’s of resume-writing, we will break out and swap resumes to gather feedback in preparation for internship and job application season.

 

Virtual Lightning Talks: Date TBD

This is an opportunity to showcase the amazing work UCSD students are doing, whether it’s a technical project, research, or extracurricular activity – we want to hear about it!

MentoriNG UCSD will be concluded with a panel of managers from NG to share their experiences and advice with students.

Name: Social Network @ UC San Diego
Description:
hello everyone! This week's meeting will be a collaborative event between the Social Network and Triple 3 V. Triple 3  V is a nonprofit organization dedicated to shining light on enterprising, resilient, and creative students. Unlike other student advocacy organizations that solely focus on academia, they spotlight a variety of fields. Through their scholarship opportunities, mentorships, and leadership summits, they help motivate students while celebrating their successes. 

The "Triple V Me" initiative provides a platform for students to share their impactful stories. Students who excel in academics, arts, community work, entrepreneurship, and sports give first-hand accounts of how they've overcome adversity and challenges head-on to get where they are. 20 of these inspiring students will be eligible to receive a scholarship of up to $3,000 to honor their tales of perseverance. 

"Triple V Community" is a project that focuses on cultivating a sense of community and promoting cultural exchange between American and Ukrainian students. It aims to create a space for Ukrainian students to connect with American students who can aid in the acclimation process. In order to encourage leadership and networking, monthly meetings will be held, featuring fun activities, guest speakers, and student led discussion.  

If anyone is interested in any of these opportunities, please fill out this form (https://forms.gle/2teeNDBXk2hv9ruF8) to attend our meeting on Saturday at 1:00 pm on October 14th at M.O.M.S. cafe. If you cannot attend in person, we will have a zoom at the same time for people to join. The zoom link will be posted before the event. For further information feel free to check out the Triple 3 V website (https://www.triple3v.org/) or contact us through one of our platforms and we will do our best to answer your questions.

Name: ACM AI at UCSD
Description:
Hi everyone! Triton Ai has a tremendous opportunity to learn from **the CEO of the Construct tomorrow 10/26/2023 from 6-8PM**, the location will be announced when the details are finalized. ***Please bring your laptop, dinner will be provided. ***

Dr. Ricardo Tellez is the CEO of The Construct (www.theconstruct.ai), the company world leader in teaching ROS online. He has a PhD in Artificial Intelligence. He has 10 years experience building software for ROS based robots including human size humanoids. 
He is the author of 4 books about learning ROS (the ROS in 5 days series of books). He teaches ROS at Technical University of Catalonia (UPC) at the Master Industria 4.0.
Additionally, he is the host of the ROS Developers Podcast, where he interviews experts of the robotics industry about how to build robots and companies with ROS.
Class plan:

1. Explain publishers and subscribers in ROS2, using the simulations 
Part 1: creating ROS2 packages
Part 2: accessing the robot motors
Part 3: accessing the lidar sensor information

2. Provide class with a project that they have to solve: get the ROSbot XL out of the maze     
* They will try to solve this in simulation of the Cyberworld (a futuristic maze we built)

3. Competition between the students: who makes the real ROSbot XL get out of the real Cyberworld 
* Then they will connect to the real Cyberworld and try there their algorithms    
* This will be a competition between the students and we'll create a ranking

Description:
Hello everyone! For those who may not know me yet, my name is Anson, and I currently serve as the Public Relations representative on the UCSD Kendo Club Board. I've made the decision to graduate early during this Winter Quarter and will be studying abroad. For situations such as these in the future, I'd like to suggest a constitutional amendment specifically addressing situations like mine, where a member cannot complete a full term but wishes to avoid leaving their position vacant. We are planning to make a minor amendment to the club constitution, and for all active club members, you are guaranteed the right to vote on this change.

In accordance with “Section 9.2: Voting on an Amendment”, I am initiating a quorum of
all currently participating members of the UCSD Kendo Club to vote on this 
amendment. Current active club members are defined as those who regularly engage in club
activities, attend practices, and pay dues as required. Should the proposed amendment garner the approval of a simple majority of the active Club members present, we will implement the proposed amendment "Section 6.4: Role Sharing." In the event that a simple majority of votes in favor is not achieved,the amendment will be deemed null and void.

The voting period will be open from 8:00 PM on October 4, 2023, to 8:00 PM on October 5,
2023. Go to this link: https://forms.gle/hjScxWwHojQh4uhx8
to submit your anonymous response. Use your UCSD account. Thank you!

The proposed amendment, "Section 6.4: Role Sharing”, is highlighted in red under “Article VI: Elections”:

Name: Sun God Archery @ UCSD
Description:
Good afternoon everyone !Just a quick announcement for those of you registered for our UCSD SIACC qual this Saturday (or those of you interested in learning how tournaments work).

Here is the official tournament guide from USA Archery:

https://www.usarchery.org/resources/event-reference-guidebook-080519202000.pdf

**If you have never competed before, please read it before Saturday! **

It goes over technicalities like format, dress code, how to score, and shooting etiquette. We have coaches and officers available on Saturday to help you through the tournament, but everyone will be extremely busy; try to cover your bases ahead of time if possible.

Also, **be at the field by 8:30am at the latest**. The first round of practice starts at 10 am but you have to get your equipment checked and figure out line assignments. Give yourself wiggle room, avoid the stress, come early! 

You can expect  to be done around 2pm. Remember to bring water and snacks/food- it might be hot. 

If you have any questions, don’t hesitate to reach out to your fellow teammates for help.

See you all on Saturday! (Or tonight if you’re getting some last minute practice in ~~like me~~)

Hi everyone! Triton Ai has a opportunity to learn from **the CEO of the Construct tomorrow 10/26/2023 from 6-8PM**, the location will be announced when the details are finalized. ***Please bring your laptop, dinner will be provided. ***

Dr. Ricardo Tellez is the CEO of The Construct (www.theconstruct.ai), the company world leader in teaching ROS online. He has a PhD in Artificial Intelligence. He has 10 years experience building software for ROS based robots including human size humanoids. 
He is the author of 4 books about learning ROS (the ROS in 5 days series of books). He teaches ROS at Technical University of Catalonia (UPC) at the Master Industria 4.0.
Additionally, he is the host of the ROS Developers Podcast, where he interviews experts of the robotics industry about how to build robots and companies with ROS.
Class plan:

1. Explain publishers and subscribers in ROS2, using the simulations 
Part 1: creating ROS2 packages
Part 2: accessing the robot motors
Part 3: accessing the lidar sensor information

2. Provide class with a project that they have to solve: get the ROSbot XL out of the maze     
* They will try to solve this in simulation of the Cyberworld (a futuristic maze we built)

3. Competition between the students: who makes the real ROSbot XL get out of the real Cyberworld 
* Then they will connect to the real Cyberworld and try there their algorithms    
* This will be a competition between the students and we'll create a ranking

Please fill out this form to reserve your spot:https://forms.gle/xTZ8FFfyeA9b3hhC6

Hey everyone, Applications for Robocup Soccer are now open! Robocup is one of IEEE's annual projects where we build a team of autonomous soccer-playing robots to compete globally against other universities. We compete in the small-size league and are planning on competing in the Netherlands this summer.

Robocup is an initiative created with the objective to defeat the human World Cup champions by 2050 and has created a large community, including undergraduate and graduate students and professors from top universities worldwide as well as professionals and companies like Google, all collaborating on technologies such as computer vision, humanoid robots, and more.

We are recruiting for highly-motivated and dedicated students for both our software and mechatronics teams who are interested in AI, embedded design, robotics, CAD, and more. Description:
Hello everyone! Engineers for Explorations (E4E) is a research opportunity for undergraduate students. Applications for the Fall Quarter are now open! Directed by Professor Curt Schurgers (ECE) and Professor Ryan Kastner (CSE), E4E aims to develop technologies for researchers in fields like oceanography, ecology, conservation, and more! E4E hosts a variety of projects from from using lasers and cameras to measure fish lengths, machine learning to detect bird calls from soundscapes and mangroves via satellite imagery, improving radio tracking for wildlife, to turning surfboard fins into coastal sensor arrays along the coastline!

If you are interested in learning more, see our website at https://e4e.ucsd.edu. To apply, fill out our app at https://e4e.ucsd.edu/join (deadline is Oct 15th at 6 pm).

Finally on Tuesday, October 10th at 4 PM in CSE 1242 we are holding an info session so you can learn more about the projects and the students leading them! Hope to see everyone there!

Dr. Ricardo Tellez is the CEO of The Construct (www.theconstruct.ai), the company world leader in teaching ROS online. He has a PhD in Artificial Intelligence. He has 10 years experience building software for ROS based robots including human size humanoids. 
He is the author of 4 books about learning ROS (the ROS in 5 days series of books). He teaches ROS at Technical University of Catalonia (UPC) at the Master Industria 4.0.
Additionally, he is the host of the ROS Developers Podcast, where he interviews experts of the robotics industry about how to build robots and companies with ROS.
Class plan:

1. Explain publishers and subscribers in ROS2, using the simulations 
Part 1: creating ROS2 packages
Part 2: accessing the robot motors
Part 3: accessing the lidar sensor information

2. Provide class with a project that they have to solve: get the ROSbot XL out of the maze

3. Competition between the students: who makes the real ROSbot XL get out of the real Cyberworld

Name: UCSD Badminton Team
Description:
🏸Welcome to UCSD Badminton!🏸 

Hello hello this is our official discord server for the UCSD Badminton Team! We kindly ask for you to read and abide by the following rules to keep the server a safe and welcoming community. 

If you have any concerns regarding another member who you feel is acting inappropriately, please contact anybody with an captains role.

1) Be respectful
2) Don't spam
3) No NSFW and use common sense
4) Keep content in relevant channels

Feel free to grab some roles in ⁠get-roles, you will be able to get pinged for our socials and tournaments there.

🏸 Our practice times are:
 - Wednesday 8-11 PM  Main Gym and Rec Gym
 - Sunday 7-11 PM  Main Gym and Rec Gym

🏸 IN ORDER TO BE ABLE TO PLAY
 - You must be signed up on DSE 
https://ucsd.dserec.com/online/clubsports_widget/
 - Pay membership dues here
https://forms.gle/8MYk5PyCnpUUKFre6

🏸 Follow us on Social Media!
https://linktr.ee/ucsdbadminton

🏸FAQS
Does the club provide rackets?
- No, the club does not have rackets 😦 we are poor. Main gym has 4 rental rackets for open gym free play just bring your student ID and if you are lucky you can borrow those. Many club members are open to letting you borrow their rackets if you ask nicely :).

How much do club dues cost?
-  $125 for the whole year and you pay in fall quarter of that year or $45 a quarter beginning of the quarter you are paying for. Pay after you register on DSE and before you come to practice. Use the link above to pay dues. 

Do you have tryouts?
- No, we accept any skill level you just need to register to join the club!

How can I compete in league matches?
- We will host ranking during practices before league matches and those who place in the top 2-4 for that category plays for UCSD. 

How are practices ran?
- It is open play and you sign up for a court to play on, sometimes there are challenge courts where the winner stays on. We also have training in main gym starting in winter quarter.

Thanks for reading!
